{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3fc227a9-54e4-47a6-ab0c-fdf40aaabbfc","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports** are saved to:\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for `.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS) files matching your process name. You can also browse them in **Console.app → Crash Reports**.\n\n**Core dumps** (if you need a full dump):\n1. Enable them: `ulimit -c unlimited`\n2. Reproduce the crash.\n3. Check `/cores/` for `core.<pid>` files.\n\n> **Note:** SIP (System Integrity Protection) may block core dump generation. You may need to disable it in Recovery Mode, or use `lldb --attach-pid <pid>` to catch crashes live.\n\n**Quick check:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | head\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0afce5fa-b7ab-495a-8e00-933ec8011a74","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's what they need to know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user processes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system processes).\n2. Files have extensions like `.crash` or `.ips` (newer macOS versions use `.ips` JSON format).\n\n\n3. Console.app provides a convenient way to browse crash reports directly through its dedicated section.\n4. Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS, but enabling them requires setting the ulimit and checking the `/cores/` directory — though System Integrity Protection may block this approach.","outputTokens":458,"requestId":"5FC2:2CF44:D4B31E:F8063D:69EACA66"},"id":"caece340-a851-4707-8229-6aaeab151d53","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:42:10.951Z","parentId":"2484a95b-32dc-4b8f-b754-a7e79fb0a322"}
